examples/minimal-research-workflow/runs/
examples/minimal-research-workflow/outputs/



# agent-workflows installer local backups
.agent-workflows-installer-backups/

# Credentials and secrets (never commit these)
.env
.env.*
*.pem
*.key
*.p12
*.pfx
*.jks
*.keystore
.netrc
.npmrc
.pypirc
service-account*.json
credentials*.json

# Virtual environments
.venv/
venv/

# Editor state
*.swp
.vscode/

# OpenCode agent session-recovery dumps (transcripts / prompts / restart snapshots).
# These are DURABLE and worth keeping (they hold the full development reasoning), but they
# must NOT be committed: this repo is public, and the transcripts contain home paths,
# gh-auth/token discussion, private-repo names (e.g. the private JOSS paper repo), and
# other private context that a public commit would leak permanently. Kept locally / in a
# private archive instead; see the maintainer's out-of-repo archive. (OpenCode's own
# session storage lives globally under ~/.local/share/opencode/, not in the repo; this
# only guards recovery dumps that get written into the project tree.)
opencode-recovery/
# Same class, but landing in the framework's staged-prompts area: opencode session
# recovery/compacted transcript dumps (named ...-ses_<id>.compacted.md / .restart.md /
# .transcript.md / .prompt.md). `.agents/prompts/` itself is a LEGITIMATE staged-prompt
# area (release-review reads it), so ignore ONLY the recovery-dump files, not the dir.
.agents/prompts/**/*-ses_*.compacted.md
.agents/prompts/**/*-ses_*.restart.md
.agents/prompts/**/*-ses_*.transcript.md
.agents/prompts/**/*-ses_*.prompt.md

# Local machine-specific config for scripts/sanitize_paths.py (may contain a real
# hostname / home path / IP in its allow/block lists). The tracked template is
# .sanitize-local.toml.example.
.sanitize-local.toml
